Host: SachaChua

It's May and puns are great, so I'd like to suggest **"May I recommend..."** as our [[Carnival]] theme this month.

There have been a few lively conversations about people's favourite packages on [https://lobste.rs/s/sz3gab/what_are_your_favorite_emacs_packages lobste.rs], [https://www.reddit.com/r/emacs/comments/1stw78y/what_are_your_favorite_emacs_packages/ Reddit], and [https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47875031 Hacker News], and it's also a perennially popular topic with lots of insights and [https://www.jerrymichalski.com/brain439602ef resources]. In fact, [https://goritskov.com/posts/obscure_packages.html Emacs Carnival Sept 2025 "Obscure packages"] and [https://takeonrules.com/2025/08/01/emacs-carnival-2025-08-your-elevator-pitch-for-emacs/ Aug 2025 "Your Elevator Pitch for Emacs"] touch on those aspects too. Let's broaden the scope a bit: what would you recommend to other people who use Emacs close to the way you do? This might nudge you to write about:

* Your favourite workflow
* The tiny (or large!) configuration tweaks that make things so much better for you
* A keyboard shortcut you recently discovered, or one that you changed to something that you like more
* A package you like
* A recommendation you received from someone or you picked up from a discussion that opened your eyes

Here are my meta-recommendations for you:

* If you've been mostly reading all these cool Emacs blog posts but you're a little intimidated by the thought of posting an Emacs Carnival entry yourself, may I recommend that you give it a shot? We can all learn together, and it's a lot of fun. You might not feel like an expert, but that's okay, you don't have to be one. There are so many different ways of using Emacs and so many things that people use it for, so it often feels impossible to make a universal recommendation. Tell us a little about where you're coming from, and you might find that people resonate with what you recommend.

* If you're comfortable writing, but you don't have a convenient setup for screenshots or videos yet, may I recommend figuring out whatever tools and shortcuts would make it easier for you to take and share those screenshots and videos? They're a great way for people to get a sense of how things fit together. Of course, text (and possibly code) is also perfectly fine.

* This might also be a good excuse to dust off the TODOs and notes you've saved from other people's recommendations and spend some time trying things out. Who knows, you might discover a new favourite! If you let people know if their recommendation worked for you, that will probably make their day - and maybe they'll have even more recommendations.

Looking forward to reading your posts!

